## The walk — five checklist rows, each two clicks deep

### Row 1 · Full capture & retention
Open traces{{ traces_link }}: 30 days of `copilot-turn` traces, Berlin business-hours
rhythm (lunch dip, quiet Fridays, a tagged nightly batch at 03:00). Open sessions{{ sessions_link }}:
multi-turn analyst chats (median ~7 turns, the occasional 25-turn deep-dive). Open any
trace: filings_search → document_fetch → table_extract → the generation (linked to its
exact prompt version) — full metadata: release/git_sha, filing-type, desk, language.
> "Every interaction, retained and queryable — and it's ClickHouse underneath."

### Row 2 · Ground truth from real traffic
Open dataset `{{ suite_info.name }}`{{ datasets_link }}: {{ suite_info["items"] }} items tagged by scenario;
curated items carry `sourceTraceId` into real production traces. Open the queue
`{{ queue.name }}`{{ queues_link }}: {{ queue.completed }} completed human reviews, {{ queue.pending }} pending —
including **`{{ flagged.trace_id }}`**{{ flagged_link }} ({{ flagged.borrower }}: copilot said
€{{ '{:,}'.format(flagged.incumbent_figure_eur) }}, filing prints €{{ '{:,}'.format(flagged.correct_figure_eur) }};
the analyst's words are on the trace). **Live beat:** complete that review and promote it
into the suite (workbench → promote, or UI).
> "The suite is what production actually got asked, with a named human behind every expected answer."

### Row 3 · Automated evaluation
Open the golden trace **numeric hallucination** (`{{ golden_map.numeric_hallucination.trace_id }}`):
the answer misstates the figure vs. the filing table — `numeric_accuracy = fail` with the
arithmetic in the comment, judge `groundedness` 0.41, and the human annotation scoring
the same criteria (`numeric_accuracy = fail`, comment carrying the corrected value).
Three independent instruments, one wrong answer. Contrast with **citation gap**
(`{{ golden_map.citation_gap.trace_id }}`): fluent answer, `groundedness` fine,
`citation_coverage` 0.32 — the judge catches what a skim would not.
> "Deterministic assertions where arithmetic decides; judges where prose does; humans where it matters."

### Row 4 · Comparative certification (the heart)
Open `{{ suite_info.name }}` → **Runs**: three runs on the same suite, same expected outputs.
- `{{ baseline.name }}` — production release, passes every gate
- `{{ cand_a.name }}` — passes, groundedness ↑ (~0.94 vs ~0.91), cost ↓
- `{{ cand_b.name }}` — **numeric_lookup {{ '%.1f%%'|format((cand_b.pass_rates or {}).get('numeric_lookup', 0)*100) }} vs ≥{{ '%.0f%%'|format(gates.get('numeric_lookup', 0.95)*100) }} → REJECTED**

Drill into one of candidate B's red items: the `numeric_accuracy` comment states exactly
which figure diverged from the printed table. A real decision, on screen: ship A, reject B.
> "Certification of any change — model, prompt, parameters — is an experiment run, not a six-week project."

### Row 5 · One evidence trail
Open scores{{ scores_link }} and filter: `numeric_accuracy` (deterministic), `groundedness` /
`citation_coverage` (judge + human — the review queue binds the SAME criteria configs, so
annotators score the certification scales to create ground truth; human entries carry the
'human annotation' comment), `analyst_feedback` (user) — one surface, co-filterable across
production traces AND experiment runs.
On queue-completed traces, judge and human sit side by side (~88% agreement, visible
disagreements — that's realism, not noise).
> "Human, judge, deterministic, and user feedback — one scores surface, one audit trail."

### The landing line
> "Production feeds the ground truth; ground truth feeds the experiments; experiments
> certify the release — prompt + parameters + model. Monitoring keeps watching, and any
> change re-enters the same pipeline. That used to be manual and slow; you just watched it."

